# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-formats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-formats/bitmap] In computing, a **bitmap** (also called **raster**) graphic is an image formed from rows of different colored pixels.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] A GIF is an example of a graphics image file that uses a bitmap.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] As a noun, the term "bitmap" is very often used to refer to a particular bitmapping application: the **pix-map**, which refers to a map of pixels, where each pixel may store more than two colors, thus using more than one bit per pixel.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] In such a case, the domain in question is the array of pixels which constitute a digital graphic output device (a screen or monitor).
[src:image-formats/bitmap] In some contexts, the term *bitmap* implies one bit per pixel, whereas *pixmap* is used for images with multiple bits per pixel.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] A bitmap is a type of memory organization or image file format used to store digital images.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] The term *bitmap* comes from the computer programming terminology, meaning just a *map of bits*, a spatially mapped array of bits.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Now, along with *pixmap*, it commonly refers to the similar concept of a spatially mapped array of pixels.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Raster images in general may be referred to as bitmaps or pixmaps, whether synthetic or photographic, in files or memory.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Many graphical user interfaces use bitmaps in their built-in graphics subsystems.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] For example, the Microsoft Windows and OS/2 platforms' GDI subsystem uses the *Windows and OS/2 bitmap file format*, usually named with the file extension `.BMP` (or `.DIB` for *device-independent bitmap*).
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Besides BMP, other file formats that store literal bitmaps include InterLeaved Bitmap (ILBM), Portable Bitmap (PBM), X Bitmap (XBM), and Wireless Application Protocol Bitmap (WBMP).
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Similarly, most other image file formats, such as JPEG, TIFF, PNG, and GIF, also store bitmap images (as opposed to vector graphics), but they are not usually referred to as *bitmaps*, since they use compressed formats internally.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] In typical uncompressed bitmaps, image pixels are generally stored with a variable number of bits per pixel which identify its color (the color depth).
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Pixels of 8 bits and fewer can represent either grayscale or indexed color.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] An alpha channel (for transparency) may be stored in a separate bitmap, where it is similar to a grayscale bitmap, or in a fourth channel that, for example, converts 24-bit images to 32 bits per pixel.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] The bits representing the bitmap pixels may be packed or unpacked (spaced out to byte or word boundaries), depending on the format or device requirements.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Depending on the color depth, a pixel in the picture will occupy at least *n*/8 bytes, where *n* is the bit depth.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] where width and height are given in pixels.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] In the formula above, header size and color palette size, if any, are not included.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Due to effects of row padding to align each row start to a storage unit boundary, such as a word, additional bytes may be needed.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Microsoft has defined a particular representation of color bitmaps of different color depths, as an aid to exchanging bitmaps between devices and applications with a variety of internal representations.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] They called these device-independent bitmaps "DIBs", and the file format for them is called DIB file format or BMP file format.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Here, "device independent" refers to the format, or storage arrangement, and should not be confused with device-independent color.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] The X Window System uses a similar XBM format for black-and-white images, and XPM (*pixelmap*) for color images.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Numerous other uncompressed bitmap file formats are in use, though most not widely.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] For most purposes, standardized compressed bitmap files such as GIF, PNG, TIFF, and JPEG are used.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Lossless compression in particular provides the same information as a bitmap in a smaller file size.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] TIFF is usually either uncompressed, or lossless Lempel–Ziv–Welch compressed like GIF.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] PNG uses deflate lossless compression, another Lempel-Ziv variant.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] There are also a variety of "raw" image files, which store raw bitmaps with no other information.
[src:image-formats/bitmap] Such raw files are just bitmaps in files, often with no header or size information (they are distinct from photographic raw image formats, which store raw unprocessed sensor data in a structured container such as TIFF format along with extensive image metadata).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Color depth is only one aspect of color representation, expressing the precision with which the amount of each primary can be expressed; the other aspect is how broad a range of colors can be expressed (the gamut).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The definition of both color precision and gamut is accomplished with a color encoding specification which assigns a digital code value to a location in a color space.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The number of bits of resolved intensity in a color channel is also known as **radiometric resolution**, especially in the context of satellite images.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] With the relatively low color depth, the stored value is typically a number representing the index into a color map or palette (a form of vector quantization).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The colors available in the palette itself may be fixed by the hardware or modifiable by software.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Modifiable palettes are sometimes referred to as pseudocolor palettes.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Old graphics chips, particularly those used in home computers and video game consoles, often have the ability to use a different palette per sprites and tiles in order to increase the maximum number of simultaneously displayed colors, while minimizing use of then-expensive memory (and bandwidth).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] For example, in the ZX Spectrum the picture is stored in a two-color format, but these two colors can be separately defined for each rectangular block of 8×8 pixels.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The palette itself has a color depth (number of bits per entry).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] While the best VGA systems only offered an 18-bit (262,144 color) palette from which colors could be chosen, all color Macintosh video hardware offered a 24-bit (16 million color) palette.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 24-bit palettes are nearly universal on any recent hardware or file format using them.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] If instead the color can be directly figured out from the pixel values, it is "direct color".
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Palettes were rarely used for depths greater than 12 bits per pixel, as the memory consumed by the palette would exceed the necessary memory for direct color on every pixel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 2 colors, often black and white direct color.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Sometimes 1 meant black and 0 meant white, the inverse of modern standards.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Most of the first graphics displays were of this type, the X Window System was developed for such displays, and this was assumed for a 3M computer.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] In the late 1980s there were professional displays with resolutions up to 300 dpi (the same as a contemporary laser printer) but color proved more popular.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 4 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Gray-scale early NeXTstation, color Macintoshes, Atari ST medium resolution.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 8 colors, almost always all combinations of full-intensity red, green, and blue.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Many early home computers with TV displays, including the ZX Spectrum and BBC Micro.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 16 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Used by IBM CGA (at the lowest resolution), EGA, and by the least common denominator VGA standard at higher resolution.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Color Macintoshes, Atari ST low resolution, Commodore 64, and Amstrad CPCs also supported 4-bit color.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 32 colors from a programmable palette, used by the Original Amiga chipset.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Used by the Master System, Enhanced Graphics Adapter, GIME for TRS-80 Color Computer 3, Pebble Time smartwatch (64 color e-paper display), and Parallax Propeller using the reference VGA circuit.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 256 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette: Most early color Unix workstations, Super VGA, color Macintosh, Atari TT, Amiga AGA chipset, Falcon030, Acorn Archimedes.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Both X and Windows provided elaborate systems to try to allow each program to select its own palette, often resulting in incorrect colors in any window other than the one with focus.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some systems placed a color cube in the palette for a direct-color system (and so all programs would use the same palette).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Usually fewer levels of blue were provided than others, since the normal human eye is less sensitive to the blue component than to either red or green (two thirds of the eye's receptors process the longer wavelengths).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 4,096 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette (though it was often set to a 16×16×16 color cube).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some Silicon Graphics systems, Color NeXTstation systems, and Amiga systems in HAM mode have this color depth.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] RGBA4444, a related 16 bpp representation providing the color cube and 16 levels of transparency, is a common texture format in mobile graphics.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] In high-color systems, two bytes (16 bits) are stored for each pixel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Most often, each component (R, G, and B) is assigned 5 bits, plus one unused bit (or used for a mask channel or to switch to indexed color); this allows 32,768 colors to be represented.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However, an alternate assignment which reassigns the unused bit to the G channel allows 65,536 colors to be represented, but without transparency.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] These color depths are sometimes used in small devices with a color display, such as mobile phones, and are sometimes considered sufficient to display photographic images.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Among the first hardware to use the standard were the Sharp X68000 and IBM's Extended Graphics Array (XGA).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The term "high color" has recently been used to mean color depths greater than 24 bits.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] More expensive LCDs (typically IPS) can display 24-bit color depth or greater.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 24 bits almost always use 8 bits each of R, G, and B (8 bpc).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] As of 2018, 24-bit color depth is used by virtually every computer and phone display and the vast majority of image storage formats.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Almost all cases of 32 bits per pixel assigns 24 bits to the color, and the remaining 8 for the alpha channel (transparency) or left unused.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] While human eye can discriminate up to ten million colors, color gamuts employed by displays are typically smaller than the range of human vision.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] This means that 24 bits should be able to differentiate different colors with enough precision to prevent the perception of banding.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However, displays do not evenly distribute the colors in human perception space, so banding between some adjacent colors can still be perceived.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The DVD-Video and Blu-ray Disc standards support a bit depth of 8 bits per color in YCbCr with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] YCbCr can be losslessly converted to RGB.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] macOS and Classic Mac OS refer to 24-bit color as "millions" of colors.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The term *true color* is sometimes used to mean what this article calls *direct color*.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] It is also often used to refer to all color depths greater than or equal to 24 bits.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some earlier systems placed three 10-bit channels in a 32-bit word, with 2 bits unused (or used as a 4-level alpha channel); the Cineon file format, for example, used this.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some SGI systems had 10-bit (or more) digital-to-analog converters for the video signal and could be set up to interpret data stored this way for display.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] BMP files define this as one of its formats, and it is called "HiColor" by Microsoft.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Video cards with 10 bits per component started coming to market in the late 1990s.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] An early example was the Radius ThunderPower card for the Macintosh, which included extensions for QuickDraw and Adobe Photoshop plugins to support editing 30-bit images.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some vendors call their 24-bit color depth with FRC panels 30-bit panels; however, true deep color displays have 10-bit or more color depth without FRC.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The HDMI 1.3 specification defines a bit depth of 30 bits (as well as 36 and 48 bit depths).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] As of 2026, 30 and 36 bit output is supported by all modern GPUs from Nvidia, AMD and Intel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] At WinHEC 2008, Microsoft announced that color depths of 30 bits and 48 bits would be supported in Windows 7, along with the wide color gamut scRGB.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) defines the Main 10 profile, which allows for 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The Main 10 profile was added at the October 2012 HEVC meeting based on proposal JCTVC-K0109 which proposed that a 10-bit profile be added to HEVC for consumer applications.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The proposal stated that this was to allow for improved video quality and to support the Rec.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] 2020 color space that will be used by UHDTV.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The second version of HEVC has five profiles that allow for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Using 12 bits per color channel produces 36 bits, 68,719,476,736 colors.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 48 bits per pixel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 64 bits per pixel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Some systems started using those bits for numbers outside the 0–1 range rather than for increasing the resolution.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Numbers greater than 1 were for colors brighter than the display could show, as in high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI).
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Negative numbers can increase the gamut to cover all possible colors, and for storing the results of filtering operations with negative filter coefficients.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The Pixar Image Computer used 12 bits to store numbers in the range [-1.5, 2.5), with 2 bits for the integer portion and 10 for the fraction.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The Cineon imaging system used 10-bit professional video displays with the video hardware adjusted so that a value of 95 was black and 685 was white.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The amplified signal tended to reduce the lifetime of the CRT.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] More bits also encouraged the storage of light as linear values, where the number directly corresponds to the amount of light emitted.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Linear levels makes calculation of computer graphics much easier.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However, linear color results in disproportionately more samples near white and fewer near black, so the quality of 16-bit linear is about equal to 12-bit sRGB.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Floating point numbers can represent linear light levels spacing the samples semi-logarithmically.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Floating point representations also allow for drastically larger dynamic ranges as well as negative values.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Most systems first supported 32-bit per channel single-precision, which far exceeded the accuracy required for most applications.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] In 1999, Industrial Light & Magic released the open standard image file format OpenEXR which supported 16-bit-per-channel half-precision floating-point numbers.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] At values near 1.0, half precision floating point values have only the precision of an 11-bit integer value, leading some graphics professionals to reject half-precision in situations where the extended dynamic range is not needed.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Virtually all television displays and computer displays form images by varying the strength of just three primary colors: red, green, and blue.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] For example, bright yellow is formed by roughly equal red and green contributions, with no blue contribution.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] For storing and manipulating images, alternative ways of expanding the traditional triangle exist: One can convert image coding to use fictitious primaries, that are not physically possible but that have the effect of extending the triangle to enclose a much larger color gamut.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] An equivalent, simpler change is to allow negative numbers in color channels, so that the represented colors can extend out of the color triangle formed by the primaries.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However these only extend the colors that can be represented in the image encoding; neither trick extends the gamut of colors that can actually be rendered on a display device.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Supplementary colors can widen the color gamut of a display, since it is no longer limited to the interior of a triangle formed by three primaries at its corners, e.g. the CIE 1931 color space.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Recent technologies such as Texas Instruments's *BrilliantColor* augment the typical red, green, and blue channels with up to three other primaries: cyan, magenta, and yellow.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Cyan would be indicated by negative values in the red channel, magenta by negative values in the green channel, and yellow by negative values in the blue channel, validating the use of otherwise fictitious negative numbers in the color channels.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Mitsubishi and Samsung (among others) use *BrilliantColor* in some of their TV sets to extend the range of displayable colors.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The Sharp Aquos line of televisions has introduced Quattron technology, which augments the usual RGB pixel components with a yellow subpixel.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However, formats and media that allow or make use of the extended color gamut are at present extremely rare.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] Because humans are overwhelmingly trichromats or dichromats one might suppose that adding a fourth "primary" color could provide no practical benefit.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] However humans can see a broader range of colors than a mixture of three colored lights can display.
[src:image-formats/color-depth] The deficit of colors is particularly noticeable in saturated shades of bluish green (shown as the left upper grey part of the horseshoe in the diagram) of RGB displays: Most humans can see more vivid blue-greens than any color video screen can display.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] In this guide, we'll cover the image file types generally supported by web browsers, and provide insights that will help you select the most appropriate formats to use for your site's imagery.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The image file formats that are most commonly used on the web are listed below.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The following list includes image formats that appear on the web, but which should be avoided for web content (generally this is because either they do not have wide browser support, or because there are better alternatives).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The following sections provide a brief overview of each of the image file types supported by web browsers.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] In the tables below, the term **bits per component** refers to the number of bits used to represent each color component.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For example, an RGB color depth of 8 indicates that each of the red, green, and blue components are represented by an 8-bit value.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] **Bit depth**, on the other hand, is the total number of bits used to represent each pixel in memory.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] APNG is a file format first introduced by Mozilla which extends the PNG standard to add support for animated images.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Conceptually similar to the animated GIF format which has been in use for decades, APNG is more capable in that it supports a variety of color depths, whereas animated GIF supports only 8-bit indexed color.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] APNG is ideal for basic animations that do not need to synchronize to other activities or to a sound track, such as progress indicators, activity throbbers, and other animated sequences.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For example, APNG is one of the formats supported when creating animated stickers for Apple's iMessage application (and the Messages application on iOS).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] They're also commonly used for the animated portions of web browsers' user interfaces.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] AV1 is a coding format that was originally designed for video transmission over the Internet.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The format benefits from the significant advances in video encoding in recent years, and may potentially benefit from the associated support for hardware rendering.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] However it also has disadvantages for some cases, as video and image encoding have some different requirements.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] AVIF does not support progressive rendering, so files must be fully downloaded before they can be displayed.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This often has little impact on real-world user experience because AVIF files are much smaller than the equivalent JPEG or PNG files, and hence can be downloaded and displayed much faster.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For larger file size the impact can become significant, and you should consider using a format that supports progressive rendering.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] AVIF is supported in Chrome, Edge, Opera, Safari and Firefox.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] As support is not yet comprehensive (and has little historical depth) you should provide a fallback in WebP, JPEG or PNG format using the `<picture>` element (or some other approach).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The **BMP** (**Bitmap image**) file type is most prevalent on Windows computers, and is generally used only for special cases in web apps and content.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] BMP theoretically supports a variety of internal data representations.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The simplest, and most commonly used, form of BMP file is an uncompressed raster image, with each pixel occupying 3 bytes representing its red, green, and blue components, and each row padded with `0x00` bytes to a multiple of 4 bytes wide.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] While other data representations are defined in the specification, they are not widely used and often completely unimplemented.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] These features include: support for different bit depths, indexed color, alpha channels, and different pixel orders (by default, BMP is written from bottom-left corner toward the right and top, rather than from the top-left corner toward the right and bottom).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Theoretically, several compression algorithms are supported, and the image data can also be stored in JPEG or PNG format within the BMP file.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] In 1987, the CompuServe online service provider introduced the **GIF** (**Graphics Interchange Format**) image file format to provide a compressed graphics format that all members of their service would be able to use.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] GIF uses the Lempel-Ziv-Welch (LZW) algorithm to losslessly compress 8-bit indexed color graphics.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] GIF was one of the first two graphics formats supported by HTML, along with XBM.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Each pixel in a GIF is represented by a single 8-bit value serving as an index into a palette of 24-bit colors (8 bits each of red, green, and blue).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The length of a color table is always a power of 2 (that is, each palette has 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, or 256 entries).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] To simulate more than 255 or 256 colors, dithering is generally used.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] It is technically possible to tile multiple image blocks, each with its own color palette, to create true color images, but in practice this is rarely done.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Pixels are opaque, unless a specific color index is designated as transparent, in which case pixels colored that value are entirely transparent.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] GIF supports simple animation, in which following an initial full-size frame, a series of images reflecting the parts of the image that change with each frame are provided.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] GIF has been extremely popular for decades, due to its simplicity and compatibility.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Its animation support caused a resurgence in its popularity in the social media era, when animated GIFs began to be widely used for short "videos", memes, and other simple animation sequences.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Another popular feature of GIF is support for interlacing, where rows of pixels are stored out of order so that partially-received files can be displayed in lower quality.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This is particularly useful when network connections are slow.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] GIF is a good choice for simple images and animations, although converting full color images to GIF can result in unsatisfactory dithering.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Typically, modern content should use PNG for lossless *and* indexed still images, and should consider using APNG for lossless animation sequences.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The ICO (Microsoft Windows icon) file format was designed by Microsoft for desktop icons of Windows systems.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] An ICO file can contain multiple icons, and begins with a directory listing details about each.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Following the directory comes the data for the icons.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Each icon's data can be either a BMP image without the file header, or a complete PNG image (including the file header).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] If you use ICO files, you should use the BMP format, as support for PNG inside ICO files wasn't added until Windows Vista and may not be well supported.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The JPEG (typically pronounced "**jay-peg**") image format is currently the most widely used lossy compression format for still images.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] It's particularly useful for photographs; applying lossy compression to content requiring sharpness, like diagrams or charts, can produce unsatisfactory results.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] JPEG is actually a data format for compressed photos, rather than a file type.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The JFIF (**J**PEG **F**ile **I**nterchange **F**ormat) specification describes the format of the files we think of as "JPEG" images.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The PNG (pronounced "**ping**") image format uses lossless compression, while supporting higher color depths than GIF and being more efficient, as well as featuring full alpha transparency support.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] PNG is widely supported, with all major browsers offering full support for its features.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] SVG is an XML-based vector graphics format that specifies the contents of an image as a set of drawing commands that create shapes, lines, apply colors, filters, and so forth.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] SVG files are ideal for diagrams, icons, and other images which can be accurately drawn at any size.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] As such, SVG is popular for user interface elements in modern Web design.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] SVG files are text files containing source code that, when interpreted, draws the desired image.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] An SVG image can be embedded in HTML using elements such as `<iframe>`, `<object>` and `<embed>`.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] It is possible to use SVG images anywhere where other image types can be used, including with the `<img>` element, the `background-image` CSS property, and so forth.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] However, there are additional restrictions when SVG is used in this way.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] SVG is an ideal choice for images which can be represented using a series of drawing commands, especially if the size at which the image will be rendered is unknown or may vary, since SVG will smoothly scale to the desired size.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] It's not generally useful for strictly bitmap or photographic images, although it is possible to include bitmap images within an SVG.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] TIFF is a raster graphics file format which was created to store scanned photos, although it can be any kind of image.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] It is a somewhat "heavy" format, in that TIFF files have a tendency to be larger than images in other formats.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This is because of the metadata often included, as well as the fact that most TIFF images are either uncompressed or use compression algorithms that still leave fairly large files after compression.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] TIFF supports a variety of compression methods, but the most commonly used are the CCITT Group 4 (and, for older fax systems, Group 3) compression systems used for by fax software, as well as LZW and lossy JPEG compression.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This allows different data types to be used for the same properties.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For example, the width of an image, `ImageWidth`, is stored using tag `0x0100`, and is a one-entry array.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] A single TIFF file can contain multiple images; this may be used to represent multi-page documents, for example (such as a multi-page scanned document, or a received fax).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] However, software reading TIFF files is only required to support the first image.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] TIFF supports a variety of color spaces, not just RGB.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] These include CMYK, YCbCr, and others, making TIFF a good choice for storing images intended for print, film, or television media.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Other than Safari, browsers do not natively support TIFF images in web content except by using special libraries or browser add-ons.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] As such, TIFF files are not broadly used for displaying web content, *but* it's common to provide downloadable TIFF files when distributing photos and other artwork intended for precision editing or printing.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] WebP supports lossy compression via predictive coding based on the VP8 video codec, and lossless compression that uses substitutions for repeating data.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Lossy WebP images are on average 25–35% smaller than JPEG images of visually similar compression levels.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Lossless WebP images are typically 26% smaller than the same images in PNG format.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] WebP also supports animation: in a lossy WebP file, the image data is represented by a VP8 bitstream, which may contain multiple frames.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Lossless WebP holds the `ANIM` chunk, which describes the animation, and the `ANMF` chunk, which represents a frame of an animation sequence.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] WebP now has broad support in the latest versions of major web browsers, although it does not have deep historical support.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Provide a fallback in either JPEG or PNG format, such as with the `<picture>` element.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] XBM (X Bitmap) files were the first to be supported on the Web, but are no longer used and should be avoided, as their format has potential security concerns.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Modern browsers have not supported XBM files in many years, but when dealing with older content, you may find some still around.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] XBM uses a snippet of C code to represent the contents of the image as an array of bytes.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Each image consists of 2 to 4 `#define` directives, providing the width and height of the bitmap (and optionally the hotspot, if the image is designed as a cursor), followed by an array of `unsigned char`, where each value contains 8 1-bit monochrome pixels.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] The image must be a multiple of 8 pixels wide.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Picking the best image format for your needs is likely easier than video formats, as there are fewer options with broad support, and each tends to have a specific set of use-cases.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Photographs typically fare well with lossy compression (depending on the encoder's configuration).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This makes JPEG and WebP good choices for photographs, with JPEG being more compatible but WebP perhaps offering better compression.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] To maximize quality and minimize download time, consider providing both using a fallback with WebP as the first choice and JPEG as the second.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Otherwise, JPEG is the safe choice for compatibility.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For smaller images such as icons, use a lossless format to avoid loss of detail in a size-constrained image.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] While lossless WebP is ideal for this purpose, support is not widespread yet, so PNG is a better choice unless you offer a fallback.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] If your image contains fewer than 256 colors, GIF is an option, although PNG often compresses even smaller with its indexed compression option (PNG-8).
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] If the icon can be represented using vector graphics, consider SVG, since it scales across various resolutions and sizes, so it's perfect for responsive design.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Although SVG support is good, it may be worth offering a PNG fallback for older browsers.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Unless you're willing to compromise on quality, you should use a lossless format for screenshots.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] This is particularly important if there's any text in your screenshot, as text easily becomes fuzzy and unclear under lossy compression.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] PNG is probably your best bet, but lossless WebP is arguably going to be better compressed.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] For any image that can be represented using vector graphics, SVG is the best choice.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] Otherwise, you should use a lossless format like PNG.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] If you do choose a lossy format, such as JPEG or lossy WebP, carefully weigh the compression level to avoid causing text or other shapes to become fuzzy or unclear.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] While the standard HTML `<img>` element doesn't support compatibility fallbacks for images, the `<picture>` element does.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] `<picture>` is used as a wrapper for a number of `<source>` elements, each specifying a version of the image in a different format or under different media conditions, as well as an `<img>` element which defines where to display the image and the fallback to the default or "most compatible" version.
[src:image-formats/formats-image-types] You can specify as many `<source>`s as you wish, though typically 2 or 3 is all you need.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] An **image file format** is a file format for a digital image.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] There are many formats that can be used, such as JPEG, PNG, and GIF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Most formats up until 2022 were for storing 2D images, not 3D ones.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The data stored in an image file format may be compressed or uncompressed.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] If the data is compressed, it may be done so using lossy compression or lossless compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] For graphic design applications, vector formats are often used.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Some image file formats support transparency.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] A 3D image can be represented within a 2D format, as in a stereogram or autostereogram, but this 3D image will not be a true light field, and thereby may cause the vergence–accommodation conflict.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Image files are composed of digital data in one of these formats so that the data can be displayed on a digital (computer) display or printed out using a printer.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] A common method for displaying digital image information has historically been rasterization.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The size of raster image files is positively correlated with the number of pixels in the image and the color depth (bits per pixel).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Images can be compressed in various ways, however.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] A compression algorithm stores either an exact representation or an approximation of the original image in a smaller number of bytes that can be expanded back to its uncompressed form with a corresponding decompression algorithm.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Images with the same number of pixels and color depth can have very different compressed file sizes.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Considering exactly the same compression, number of pixels, and color depth for two images, different graphical complexity of the original images may also result in very different file sizes after compression due to the nature of compression algorithms.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] With some compression formats, images that are less complex may result in smaller compressed file sizes.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] This characteristic sometimes results in a smaller file size for some lossless formats than lossy formats.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] For example, graphically simple images (i.e., images with large continuous regions like line art or animation sequences) may be losslessly compressed into a GIF or PNG format and result in a smaller file size than a lossy JPEG format.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] With vector images, the file size increases only with the addition of more vectors.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] There are two types of image file compression algorithms: lossless and lossy.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Lossless compression algorithms reduce file size while preserving a perfect copy of the original uncompressed image.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Lossless compression generally, but not always, results in larger files than lossy compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Lossless compression should be used to avoid accumulating stages of re-compression when editing images.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Lossy compression algorithms preserve a representation of the original uncompressed image that may appear to be a perfect copy, but is not a perfect copy.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Often lossy compression is able to achieve smaller file sizes than lossless compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Most lossy compression algorithms allow for variable compression that trades image quality for file size.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Including proprietary types, there are hundreds of image file types.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The PNG, JPEG, and GIF formats are most often used to display images on the Internet.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Some of these graphic formats are listed and briefly described below, separated into the two main families of graphics: raster and vector.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Raster images are further divided into formats primarily aimed at (web) delivery (i.e., supporting relatively strong compression) versus formats primarily aimed at authoring or interchange (uncompressed or only relatively weak compression).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] In addition to straight image formats, Metafile formats are portable formats that can include both raster and vector information.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Examples are application-independent formats such as WMF and EMF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The metafile format is an intermediate format.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Most applications open metafiles and then save them in their own native format.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Page description language refers to formats used to describe the layout of a printed page containing text, objects, and images.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG (Joint Photographic Experts Group) is a lossy compression method; JPEG-compressed images are usually stored in the JFIF (JPEG File Interchange Format) or the Exif (Exchangeable Image File Format) file format.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The JPEG filename extension is JPG or JPEG.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Nearly every digital camera can save images in the JPEG format, which supports eight-bit grayscale images and 24-bit color images (eight bits each for red, green, and blue).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG applies lossy compression to images, which can result in a significant reduction of the file size.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Applications can determine the degree of compression to apply, and the amount of compression affects the visual quality of the result.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] When not too great, the compression does not noticeably affect or detract from the image's quality, but JPEG files suffer generational degradation when repeatedly edited and saved.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The GIF (Graphics Interchange Format) is in normal use limited to an 8-bit palette, or 256 colors (while 24-bit color depth is technically possible).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] GIF is most suitable for storing graphics with few colors, such as simple diagrams, shapes, logos, and cartoon-style images, as it uses LZW lossless compression, which is more effective when large areas have a single color and less effective for photographic or dithered images.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Due to GIF's simplicity and age, it achieved almost universal software support.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Due to its animation capabilities, it is still widely used to provide image animation effects, despite its low compression ratio compared to modern video formats.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The PNG (Portable Network Graphics) file format was created as a free, open-source alternative to GIF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The PNG file format supports 8-bit (256 colors) paletted images (with optional transparency for all palette colors) and 24-bit truecolor (16 million colors) or 48-bit truecolor with and without an alpha channel – while GIF supports only 8-bit palettes with a single transparent color.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Compared to JPEG, PNG excels when the image has large, uniformly colored areas.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Even for photographs – where JPEG is often the choice for final distribution since its lossy compression typically yields smaller file sizes – PNG is still well-suited to storing images during the editing process because of its lossless compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] PNG provides a patent-free replacement for GIF (though GIF is itself now patent-free) and can also replace many common uses of TIFF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Indexed-color, grayscale, and truecolor images are supported, plus an optional alpha channel.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The Adam7 interlacing allows an early preview, even when only a small percentage of the image data has been transmitted—useful in online viewing applications like web browsers.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] PNG can store gamma and chromaticity data, as well as ICC profiles, for accurate color matching on heterogeneous platforms.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Animated formats derived from PNG are MNG and APNG, which is backwards compatible with PNG and supported by most browsers.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 is a compression standard enabling both lossless and lossy storage.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The compression methods used are different from the ones in standard JFIF/JPEG; they improve quality and compression ratios, but also require more computational power to process.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG 2000 also adds features that are missing in JPEG.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It is not nearly as common as JPEG but it is used currently in professional movie editing and distribution (some digital cinemas, for example, use JPEG 2000 for individual movie frames).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] WebP is an open image format released in 2010 that uses both lossless and lossy compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It was designed by Google to reduce image file size to speed up web page loading: its principal purpose is to supersede JPEG as the primary format for photographs on the web.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] WebP is based on VP8's intra-frame coding and uses a container based on RIFF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] In 2011, Google added an "Extended File Format" allowing WebP support for animation, ICC profile, XMP and Exif metadata, and tiling.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The support for animation allowed for converting older animated GIFs to animated WebP.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The WebP container (i.e., RIFF container for WebP) allows feature support over and above the basic use case of WebP (i.e., a file containing a single image encoded as a VP8 key frame).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Most typical raster formats cannot store HDR data (32 bit floating point values per pixel component), which is why some relatively old or complex formats are still predominant here, and worth mentioning separately.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Newer alternatives are showing up, though.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] RGBE is the format for HDR images originating from Radiance and also supported by Adobe Photoshop.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG-HDR is a file format from Dolby Labs similar to RGBE encoding, standardized as JPEG XT Part 2.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG XT Part 7 includes support for encoding floating point HDR images in the base 8-bit JPEG file using enhancement layers encoded with four profiles (A-D); Profile A is based on the RGBE format and Profile B on the XDepth format from Trellis Management.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The High Efficiency Image File Format (HEIF) is an image container format that was standardized by MPEG on the basis of the ISO base media file format.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] While HEIF can be used with any image compression format, the HEIF standard specifies the storage of HEVC intra-coded images and HEVC-coded image sequences taking advantage of inter-picture prediction.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] AVIF is an image container, that is used to store AV1 encoded images.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It was created by Alliance for open media (AOMedia) and is completely open source and royalty-free.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It supports encoding images in 8, 10 and 12-bit depth.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] JPEG XL is a royalty-free raster-graphics file format that supports both lossy and lossless compression.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It supports reversible recompression of existing JPEG files, as well as high-precision HDR (up to 32-bit floating point values per pixel component).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It is designed to be usable for both delivery and authoring use cases.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The TIFF (Tag Image File Format) format is a flexible format usually using either the TIFF or TIF filename extension.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The tag structure was designed to be easily extendible, and many vendors have introduced proprietary special-purpose tags – with the result that no one reader handles every flavor of TIFF file.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] TIFFs can be lossy or lossless, depending on the technique chosen for storing the pixel data.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Some offer relatively good lossless compression for bi-level (black&white) images.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Some digital cameras can save images in TIFF format, using the LZW compression algorithm for lossless storage.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] TIFF image format is not widely supported by web browsers, but it remains widely accepted as a photograph file standard in the printing business.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] TIFF can handle device-specific color spaces, such as the CMYK defined by a particular set of printing press inks.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] OCR (Optical Character Recognition) software packages commonly generate some form of TIFF image (often monochromatic) for scanned text pages.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The BMP file format (Windows bitmap) is a raster-based, device-independent file type designed in the early days of computer graphics.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It handles graphic files within the Microsoft Windows OS.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Typically, BMP files are uncompressed and therefore large and lossless; their advantage is their simple structure and wide acceptance in Windows programs.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Netpbm format is a family including the portable pixmap file format (PPM), the portable graymap file format (PGM), and the portable bitmap file format (PBM).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] These are either pure ASCII files or raw binary files with an ASCII header that provide very basic functionality and serve as a lowest common denominator for converting pixmap, graymap, or bitmap files between different platforms.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Several applications refer to them collectively as PNM (Portable Any Map).
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] As opposed to the raster image formats above (where the data describes the characteristics of each individual pixel), vector image formats contain a geometric description which can be rendered smoothly at any desired display size.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] At some point, all vector graphics must be rasterized in order to be displayed on digital monitors.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Vector images may also be displayed with analog CRT technology such as that used in some electronic test equipment, medical monitors, radar displays, laser shows and early video games.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Plotters are printers that use vector data rather than pixel data to draw graphics.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] CGM (Computer Graphics Metafile) is a file format for 2D vector graphics, raster graphics, and text, and is defined by ISO/IEC 8632.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] All graphical elements can be specified in a textual source file that can be compiled into a binary file or one of two text representations.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] CGM provides a means of graphics data interchange for computer representation of 2D graphical information independent from any particular application, system, platform, or device.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It has been adopted to some extent in the areas of technical illustration and professional design, but has largely been superseded by formats such as SVG and DXF.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The Gerber format (aka Extended Gerber, RS-274X) is a 2D bi-level image description format developed by Ucamco.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] It is the de facto standard format for printed circuit board or PCB software.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics) is an open standard created and developed by the World Wide Web Consortium to address the need (and attempts of several corporations) for a versatile, scriptable and all-purpose vector format for the web and otherwise.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] The SVG format does not have a compression scheme of its own, but due to the textual nature of XML, an SVG graphic can be compressed using a program such as gzip.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] Because of its scripting potential, SVG is a key component in web applications: interactive web pages that look and act like applications.
[src:image-formats/image-file-format] These are formats containing both pixel and vector data, possible other data, e.g. the interactive features of PDF.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] In computer graphics and digital photography, a **raster graphic**, **raster image**, or simply **raster** is a digital image made up of a rectangular grid of tiny colored (usually square) so-called pixels.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Unlike vector graphics which use mathematical formulas to describe shapes and lines, raster images store the exact color of each pixel, making them ideal for photographs and images with complex colors and details.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Raster images are characterized by their dimensions (width and height in pixels) and color depth (the number of bits per pixel).
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] They can be displayed on computer displays, printed on paper, or viewed on other media, and are stored in various image file formats.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The printing and prepress industries know raster graphics as **contones** (from "continuous tones").
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] In contrast, *line art* is usually implemented as vector graphics in digital systems.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Many raster manipulations map directly onto the mathematical formalisms of linear algebra, where mathematical objects of matrix structure are of central concern.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Raster or **gridded data** may be the result of a gridding procedure.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The word "raster" has its origins in the Latin *rastrum* (a rake), which is derived from *radere* (to scrape).
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] It originates from the raster scan of cathode-ray tube (CRT) video monitors, which draw the image line by line by magnetically or electrostatically steering a focused electron beam.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] By association, it can also refer to a rectangular grid of pixels.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The modern word rastrum refers to a device for drawing musical staff lines.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The fundamental strategy underlying the raster data model is the tessellation of a plane, into a two-dimensional array of squares, each called a *cell* or *pixel* (from "picture element").
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] In digital photography, the plane is the visual field as projected onto the image sensor; in computer art, the plane is a virtual canvas; in geographic information systems, the plane is a projection of the Earth's surface.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The size of each square pixel, known as the *resolution* or *support*, is constant across the grid.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] A single numeric value is then stored for each pixel.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] For most images, this value is a visible color, but other measurements are possible, even numeric codes for qualitative categories.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Each raster grid has a specified *pixel format*, the data type for each number.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Common pixel formats are binary, grayscale, palettized, and full-color, where color depth determines the fidelity of the colors represented, and color space determines the range of color coverage (which is often less than the full range of human color vision).
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Most modern color raster formats represent color using 24 bits (over 16 million distinct colors), with 8 bits (values 0–255) for each color channel (red, green, and blue).
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The digital sensors used for remote sensing and astronomy are often able to detect and store wavelengths beyond the visible spectrum; the large CCD bitmapped sensor at the Vera C.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Rubin Observatory captures 3.2 gigapixels in a single image (6.4 GB raw), over six color channels which exceed the spectral range of human color vision.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Most computer images are stored in raster graphics formats or compressed variations, including GIF, JPEG, and PNG, which are popular on the World Wide Web.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] A **raster data** structure is based on a (usually rectangular, square-based) tessellation of the 2D plane into cells, each containing a single value.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] To store the data in a file, the two-dimensional array must be serialized.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The most common way to do this is a *row-major* format, in which the cells along the first (usually top) row are listed left to right, followed immediately by those of the second row, and so on.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] In the example at right, the cells of tessellation A are overlaid on the point pattern B resulting in an array C of quadrant counts representing the number of points in each cell.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] For purposes of visualization a lookup table has been used to color each of the cells in an image D.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] To reconstruct the two-dimensional grid, the file must include a *header* section at the beginning that contains at least the number of columns, and the pixel datatype (especially the number of bits or bytes per value) so the reader knows where each value ends to start reading the next one.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Headers may also include the number of rows, georeferencing parameters for geographic data, or other metadata tags, such as those specified in the Exif standard.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] High-resolution raster grids contain a large number of pixels, and thus consume a large amount of storage.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] This has led to multiple approaches to compressing the data volume into smaller files.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The most common strategy is to look for patterns or trends in the pixel values, then store a parameterized form of the pattern instead of the original data.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Common raster compression algorithms include run-length encoding (RLE), JPEG, LZ (the basis for PNG and ZIP), Lempel–Ziv–Welch (LZW) (the basis for GIF), and others.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] For example, Run length encoding looks for repeated values in the array, and replaces them with the value and the number of times it appears.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] This technique is very efficient when there are large areas of identical values, such as a line drawing, but in a photograph where pixels are usually slightly different from their neighbors, the RLE file would be up to twice the size of the original.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Some compression algorithms, such as RLE and LZW, are *lossless*, where the original pixel values can be perfectly regenerated from the compressed data.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Other algorithms, such as JPEG, are *lossy*, because the parameterized patterns are only an approximation of the original pixel values, so the latter can only be estimated from the compressed data.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Vector images (line work) can be rasterized (converted into pixels), and raster images vectorized (raster images converted into vector graphics), by software.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] In both cases, some information is lost, although certain vectorization operations can recreate salient information, as in the case of optical character recognition.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Early mechanical televisions developed in the 1920s employed rasterization principles.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Electronic television based on cathode-ray tube displays are raster scanned with horizontal rasters painted left to right, and the raster lines painted top to bottom.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Modern flat-panel displays such as LED monitors still use a raster approach.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Each on-screen pixel directly corresponds to a small number of bits in memory.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The screen is refreshed simply by scanning through pixels and coloring them according to each set of bits.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The refresh procedure, being speed critical, is often implemented by dedicated circuitry, often as a part of a graphics processing unit.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Using this approach, the computer contains an area of memory that holds all the data that are to be displayed.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The central processor writes data into this region of memory and the video controller collects them from there.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The bits of data stored in this block of memory are related to the eventual pattern of pixels that will be used to construct an image on the display.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] An early scanned display with raster computer graphics was invented in the late 1960s by A.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Michael Noll at Bell Labs, but its patent application filed February 5, 1970, was abandoned at the Supreme Court in 1977 over the issue of the patentability of computer software.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] During the 1970s and 1980s, pen plotters, using vector graphics, were common for creating precise drawings, especially on large format paper.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] However, since then almost all printers create the printed image as a raster grid, including both laser and inkjet printers.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] When the source information is vector, rendering specifications and software such as PostScript are used to create the raster image.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Three-dimensional voxel raster graphics are employed in video games and are also used in medical imaging such as MRI scanners.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Geographic phenomena are commonly represented in a raster format in GIS.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The raster grid is *georeferenced*, so that each pixel (commonly called a *cell* in GIS because the "picture" part of "pixel" is not relevant) represents a square region of geographic space.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] The value of each cell then represents some measurable (qualitative or quantitative) property of that region, typically conceptualized as a field.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Examples of fields commonly represented in rasters include: temperature, population density, soil moisture, land cover, surface elevation, etc.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Two sampling models are used to derive cell values from the field: in a *lattice*, the value is measured at the center point of each cell; in a *grid*, the value is a summary (usually a mean or mode) of the value over the entire cell.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Raster graphics are resolution dependent, meaning they cannot scale up to an arbitrary resolution without loss of apparent quality.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] This property contrasts with the capabilities of vector graphics, which easily scale up to the quality of the device rendering them.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Raster graphics deal more practically than vector graphics with photographs and photo-realistic images, while vector graphics often serve better for typesetting or for graphic design.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Typically, a resolution of 150 to 300 PPI works well for 4-color process (CMYK) printing.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] However, for printing technologies that perform color mixing through dithering (halftone) rather than through overprinting (virtually all home/office inkjet and laser printers), printer DPI and image PPI have a very different meaning, and this can be misleading.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Because, through the dithering process, the printer builds a single image pixel out of several printer dots to increase color depth, the printer's DPI setting must be set far higher than the desired PPI to ensure sufficient color depth without sacrificing image resolution.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Thus, for instance, printing an image at 250 PPI may actually require a printer setting of 1200 DPI.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] When an image is rendered in a raster-based image editor, the image is composed of millions of pixels.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] At its core, a raster image editor works by manipulating each individual pixel.
[src:image-formats/raster-graphics] Most pixel-based image editors work using the RGB color model, but some also allow the use of other color models, such as the CMYK color model.
